===Alternative forms===
* {{alt|en|hivernate|hybernate}} {{q|both obsolete}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*ǵʰey-}}
From {{uder|en|la|hībernātus}}, from {{m|la|hībernō|hībernāre}}, from {{m|la|hībernus||winter}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈhaɪbəˌneɪt/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-hibernate.wav|Audio (Southern England)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|biology}} To spend the [[winter]] in a [[dormant]] or [[inactive]] state of [[minimal]] activity, low [[body temperature]], slow [[breathing]] and [[heart rate]], and low [[metabolic rate]]; to go through a winter [[sleep]].
#: {{cot|en|estivate}}
#: {{ux|en|Hedgehogs and bears are two of the many mammals that '''hibernate''' in winter.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title={{w|The Sixth Extinction: An Unnatural History}}|year=2014|author={{w|Elizabeth Kolbert}}|publisher=Henry Holt and Company|chapter=8|passage=Organisms have developed all sorts of ways of dealing with these variations. They '''hibernate''' or estivate or migrate.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To live in [[seclusion]].
# {{lb|en|intransitive|computing}} To enter a [[standby]] state which conserves power without losing the contents of [[memory]].
#* '''2001''', Microsoft Corp, ''Use Hibernate and Standby to Conserve Batteries''
#*: Your computer '''hibernates''' after it has been idle for the specified amount of time.

